  1. Research question: What weather observations are the best predictors for increased wildfire start risk in California?

I am using data from an engineered data set that combines meteorological data from NOAA Climate Data Online with fire incident data from CAL FIRE. Specifically, it is the compilation of weather observations and wildfire data in California from 1984 to 2025.

The variables used are defined below: DATE: The date of the observation. PRECIPITATION: Daily precipitation in inches. MAX_TEMP: Maximum daily temperature in degrees Fahrenheit. MIN_TEMP: Minimum daily temperature in degrees Fahrenheit. AVG_WIND_SPEED: Average daily wind speed in mph. FIRE_START_DAY: A binary indicator (True/False) showing whether a wildfire started on that date. YEAR: The year of the observation. TEMP_RANGE: The difference between maximum and minimum temperatures, indicating daily temperature variability. WIND_TEMP_RATIO: The ratio of average wind speed to maximum temperature, capturing wind-temperature dynamics. MONTH: The calendar month of the observation (1–12). SEASON: The season of the observation (Winter, Spring, Summer, Fall). LAGGED_PRECIPITATION: Cumulative precipitation over the preceding 7 days, reflecting recent moisture conditions. LAGGED_AVG_WIND_SPEED: Average wind speed over the preceding 7 days, indicating sustained wind patterns. DAY_OF_YEAR: The numeric day within the year (1–365/366).

Select a supervised learning algorithm that we haven’t discussed in class, and teach the reader how your chosen algorithm works in the context of your data:

  1. One supervised learning algorithm that has not been discussed in class and would be helpful is Support Vector Machines (SVMs). This algorithm works by finding the best line or hyper plane that separates data into groups, maximizing the distance between the closest points of each group (support vectors). When the data is not linearly separable, kernel functions, which maps data into a higher-dimensional space, are used to transform the data higher-dimensional space to enable linear separation. Kernel functions allow SVMs to operate in a higher-dimensional space by computing relationships between data points, enabling linear separation even when the original data is not linearly separable. SVM finds a hyperplane that is equidistant from the support vectors of each class, thus maximizing the margin. The margin is the space between the two dashed lines on either side of the separating hyperplane. Support vectors are the points that lie directly on these margins.

I’ve included a simple example using fake data to show how this works.

library(ggplot2)
svm_data <- data.frame(
  x = c(2, 8, 2, 3, 3, 9, 8, 7),
  y = c(0, 7, 1, 3, 1, 9, 8, 7))


svm_data |>
  ggplot(aes(y = y, x = x)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 10) +
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 6, lty = 2) +
  geom_abline(slope = -1, intercept = 14, lty = 2) +
  labs(title = "Fake Example of Splitting Two Classes") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  annotate("text", x = 1, y = 2.25, label = "group one", hjust = 0, vjust = 0) +
  annotate("text", x = 7, y = 8, label = "group two", hjust = 0, vjust = 0)

The black line represents the decision boundary, and the two dotted lines represent the margins. The points at (3, 3) and (7, 7) lie on these margins and thus are the support vectors. These support vectors are the most “influential” points for determining the boundary. Any new point above the black line would be classified as “group two”, and anything below it as “group one”.

I chose this algorithm in the context of the wildfire data because I am trying to predict binary classes (if a fire started that day or not) and Support Vector Machines does this very well. Since Support Vector Machines perform well with high-dimensional data, they are a good fit for this application involving many weather-related predictors. I would train an Support Vector Machines using this data to classify days as “fire” or “no fire” based on multiple meteorological variables. In my data set I could use variables such as precipitation, maximum temperature, or lagged average wind speed as inputs to predict if a fire started that day or not. To evaluate my precision I could chop my data in half into a training data set and a testing data set and then test the model crated on training set on the testing data set.

My first step into my investigation is to read in the data set and look at if there is missing data in any rows.

wildfire<- read.csv("/Users/giannacannek/Desktop/statistical learning/FINAL/CA_Weather_Fire_Dataset_1984-2025.csv")
md.pattern(wildfire, rotate.names = TRUE)

According to this pattern there are 14976 rows of no missing cells, 11 rows with 2 missing variables (average wind speed and wind temperature ratio), and 1 row of 6 missing variables (precipitation, maximum temperature, minimum temperature, average wind speed, and wind temperature ratio. This is a very small fraction of the data so it should not change my analysis by a lot, but it doesn’t hurt to fill in the missing data. Lets complete the data set by using a random forest! By doing this I am calculating what a missing value should be using the known variables. In this case I picked a random forest which is a combination of multiple flowchart-like models that makes predictions based on a series of decisions.

imputed_wildfires <- mice(wildfire,
                         method = "rf",
                         seed = 1)
wildfires <- complete(imputed_wildfires) ##WILDFIRE CHANGES TO WILDFIRES HERE
md.pattern(wildfires, rotate.names = TRUE)

My first statistical learning technique will be a classification decision tree to understand the importance of different variables. Decision trees recursively split data based on the most informative features and create nodes that represent decision points and leaf nodes that represent the final classification. In this case weather factors are the informative features and the final classification is if it will be a fire start day or not. For this I took out all temporal variables such as date, season, and year because those are not specific weather related variables.

no_date_wildfire <- wildfires |>
  dplyr::select(PRECIPITATION,MAX_TEMP, MIN_TEMP, AVG_WIND_SPEED, FIRE_START_DAY, TEMP_RANGE, WIND_TEMP_RATIO, LAGGED_PRECIPITATION,LAGGED_AVG_WIND_SPEED)

wildfires_tree <- rpart( FIRE_START_DAY ~ ., 
                  data = no_date_wildfire)
rpart.plot(wildfires_tree, main = "Decision Tree for Predicting Fire Start Days")

It looks like minimum temperature, lagged average wind speed, lagged precipitation, and maximum temperature are the most important variables when predicting fire start days (“True” values) because those are the deciding factors at each node. This tree agrees with the visualizations I made before as higher minimum temperature correlates with a higher ratio of fire start days in a seasonal cycle. Same with the inverse relationship of precipitation, although in this case lagged precipitation is more important than the precipitation of that singular day.

Decision tree performs well in predicting most classes, but may struggle with classes that have similar characteristics in their data. I am going to make a boosted decision tree which is an ensemble learning method that combines a set of weak learners (decision trees with less splits) into a strong learner to minimize training errors. I chose some variables that showed up in the decision trees plus maximum temperature to understand their relationship more clearly and then visualized how important their values are in predicting fire start days in a beeswarm plot.

set.seed(1)

wildfire_subset <- wildfires |>
  dplyr::select(MAX_TEMP, MIN_TEMP, LAGGED_PRECIPITATION,LAGGED_AVG_WIND_SPEED)

wildfire_subset <- wildfires |>
  dplyr::select(MAX_TEMP, MIN_TEMP, LAGGED_PRECIPITATION, LAGGED_AVG_WIND_SPEED)

label_numeric <- as.numeric(wildfires$FIRE_START_DAY == "True") 

boost_data <- xgb.DMatrix(data.matrix(wildfire_subset), label = label_numeric)

boost_model <- xgb.train(data = boost_data,
                         nrounds = 100,
                         params = list(
                           learning_rate = 0.1,
                           objective = "reg:squarederror"
                         ))

shap_values <- shapviz(boost_model, 
                       X_pred = data.matrix(wildfire_subset),
                       X = wildfire_subset)


sv_importance(shap_values, kind = "beeswarm") +
  ggtitle(" Beeswarm Plot for Wildfire Prediction Model")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5))

It looks like lagged average wind speed and minimum temperature and lagged average wind speed are very important variables as the average magnitude of SHAP values, which indicates how each feature impacts the model’s prediction, are greatest for this density. In my last model I am creating a Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) model to understand the relationship between minimum temperature and lagged average wind speed in predicting fire start day. LDA separates multiple classes (True and False) with multiple features (minimum temperature and lagged average wind speed) through data dimensional reduction. In this case I want to collapse the dimensional of minimum temperature and lagged average wind speed with fire start day. I can then find how accurate my LDA model is by splitting the data in half with equal training and testing data sets.

set.seed(1)
shuffled_wf= wildfires[sample(1:nrow(wildfires)), ] #shuffling data

training_rows <- sample(1:nrow(shuffled_wf), size = nrow(shuffled_wf)/2)

training <- shuffled_wf[training_rows, ]
testing <- shuffled_wf[-training_rows, ]

lda_test <- lda(FIRE_START_DAY ~ MIN_TEMP + LAGGED_AVG_WIND_SPEED , data = training)

test_preds <- predict(lda_test, testing)

xtab <- table(test_preds$class, testing$FIRE_START_DAY)
xtab
##        
##         False True
##   False  4206 1176
##   True    757 1349
confusionMatrix(xtab)

So therefore these two variables are significant at predicting fire start days. I am going to visualize these predictions in a grid to see how the model would respond across the full feature space every combination.

every_person_ever_grid <- expand.grid(MIN_TEMP = seq(from = 33, to = 77, by = 5),
                                      LAGGED_AVG_WIND_SPEED = seq(from = 3.227143, to = 13.93286, by = 1))

grid_preds <- predict(lda_test, every_person_ever_grid)

yes_probs <- grid_preds$posterior[,2]

library(viridis)
## Loading required package: viridisLite
every_person_ever_grid |>
  mutate(predictions = yes_probs) |>
  ggplot() +
  geom_tile(aes(x = MIN_TEMP,
                y = LAGGED_AVG_WIND_SPEED,
                fill = predictions)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "D", direction = 1) +
  labs(fill = "Prediction Probability") + 
  labs(title = "Prediction Probability Across Temperature and Wind Speed", x= "Minimum Temperature (T)", y= "Lagged Avg Wind Speed (MPH)")

The LDA analysis gradient graph agrees with the the decision tree. Higher minimum temperature in this model is correlated with an increased probability of being fire start day prediction. Based on this grid it looks like higher lagged average wind speed slightly leads to the predictions having a higher probability of wildfire start prediction.

Based on my analysis, high minimum temperature values, high wind speed, and less lagged precipitation are the best predictors of increased wildfire risk.
